Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My intuition stems from the observation that while aspect-opinion pairs are widely studied in sentiment analysis, their integration into knowledge graphs—especially in a domain-agnostic way—remains underexplored. Most existing methods either treat sentiment as flat labels or embed aspects and opinions independently, losing higher-order contextual interactions such as sentiment cascades (e.g., how one opinion influences another across entities) or latent sentiment roles (e.g., whether an opinion acts as a mitigator or amplifier). Inspired by COGMEN’s use of GNNs to model conversational context, Paper 2’s neuro-symbolic world models with memory-augmented logic, and Paper 3’s hierarchical graph embeddings for multimodal meaning, I propose a novel two-tiered neuro-symbolic framework. This framework explicitly separates *syntactic-semantic structure* (aspect-opinion dependency) from *contextual sentiment dynamics*, enabling richer modeling of sentiment propagation and interaction across domains. The key innovation lies in using symbolic logic to encode sentiment constraints (e.g., “if X praises Y’s design but criticizes usability, overall sentiment is mixed”) while learning distributed representations via GNNs over a dynamically constructed similarity graph of aspect-opinion units. Unlike prior work, this approach supports both interpretability (via logical rules) and generalization (via neural embeddings), making it truly domain-agnostic. It also introduces "sentiment proprioception"—a memory-augmented mechanism that tracks evolving sentiment states across discourse segments, akin to how agents maintain internal state in NeSA systems.

